The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
public class MultiJobResumeBuild implements RunAction2 {
```
```java
public String getIconFileName() {
    return "plugin/jenkins-multijob-plugin/tool32.png";
}
```
Reason:
The `MultiJobResumeBuild` class does not implement any permission checks, allowing any user to access the "Resume build" action. The `getIconFileName` method returns the icon without verifying if the user has the necessary administrative privileges, which exposes the action to unauthorized users.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
public class MultiJobResumeBuild implements RunAction2, StaplerProxy {
```
```java
return Jenkins.getInstance().hasPermission(Jenkins.ADMINISTER) ? "plugin/jenkins-multijob-plugin/tool32.png" : null;
```
```java
Jenkins.getInstance().checkPermission(Jenkins.ADMINISTER);
```
Reason:
The class now implements `StaplerProxy`, which allows for permission checks. The `getIconFileName` method is modified to return the icon only if the user has administrative privileges, and the `checkPermission` method is added to ensure that only authorized users can access the "Resume build" action, thus securing the functionality against unauthorized access.

